node.text: Our first ever YouTuber awards show where we celebrate those in the YouTube fishing world for what they do best.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Karl’s Bait & Tackle on July 29, 2021. May be an image of body of water and text that says 'WOULD YOU RATHER Be the person that caught the most fish of the trip Be the person that caught the biggest fish of the trip'.

node.text: And you can't say BOTH, I'm the only one who can do that 😎

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Karl’s Bait & Tackle on July 28, 2021. May be an image of text that says '4 DEEP WATER TIPS'.

node.text: If you're having trouble finding the fish right now, try looking out deep! What deep water tips do you got?⁠

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Karl’s Bait & Tackle on July 28, 2021. May be an image of text that says '4 DEEP WATER TIPS'.

Photo by Karl’s Bait & Tackle on July 28, 2021. May be an image of text that says '1. ELECTRONICS It is possible to find success out deep without electronics by researching maps or from word of mouth. But having electronics in your boat to help find ledges, drop offs, channels, deep cover, and fish, can make your life easier! They won't put fish in the boat, but can act as your eyes since you can't see down deep.'.

Photo by Karl’s Bait & Tackle on July 28, 2021. May be an image of text that says '2. MY GO-TO BAITS Carolina Rig or Football Jig: Let's you get to the bottom quickly. Deep Diving Crankbait: For aggressive fish, or to wake up inactive fish. Drop Shot or Shakey Head: Finesse rigs for for finicky fish. Spinnerbait or Big Spoon: Mimics baitfish or dying baitfish.'.

Photo by Karl’s Bait & Tackle on July 28, 2021. May be an image of text that says '3. THE BOTTOM Now not every time, but in a lot of cases fish will hug the bottom out deep. It's where the structure and cover is to protect them. So, make sure you let your bait sink all the way, and try to keep it down there. Even when fishing a crankbait, digging the lip into the bottom can stir up activity and draw in strikes.'.

Photo by Karl’s Bait & Tackle on July 28, 2021. May be an image of one or more people, beard and text that says '4. PRACTICE |proise this isn't a throw away tip, it really is the best way to get better. In deep water you can't see your bait, you have to visualize it in your head and feel it through your fishing rod. You can only learn that from time out on the water!'.

Photo by Karl’s Bait & Tackle on July 28, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'KARL'S POWER RANKINGS MONTHS with the BEST FISHING 1. April 2. October 3. May 4. September 5. August 6. March 7. June 8. July 9. November 10. February 11. December 12. January'.

node.text: Agree or disagree....

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Karl’s Bait & Tackle on July 27, 2021. May be an image of body of water.

node.text: The @googansquad MICRO CRANKS ARE LIVE IN MY SHOP! Perfect for pressured fish, pond fishing or panfishing, the micro banger, klutch, and recon are available now in the link in my bio!

node.text: When do you like to pull out the crank?

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Karl’s Bait & Tackle on July 27, 2021. May be an image of ‎text that says '‎ی 3 YEAR ROUND CRANKBAIT TIPS‎'‎.

Photo by Karl’s Bait & Tackle on July 27, 2021. May be an image of text that says '1. WHEN IN DOUBT, GO DEEPER Try crankbaits that dive slightly deeper than the desired depth. This causes it to dive into the bottom like a fleeing baitfish. It also kicks up dirt, leaving behind a trail of visual distress.'.

Photo by Karl’s Bait & Tackle on July 27, 2021. May be an image of text that says '2.LINE LINE SIZE MATTERS Experiment with your line si size to achieve the action and running depth you want. The thinner thinner the line diameter the deeper they typically run. Also, remember that a lighter line will increase your casting distance. tance'.

Photo by Karl’s Bait & Tackle on July 27, 2021. May be an image of text that says '3. 3.FISH FISH EM FAST Fish fast and cover a lot of water to trigger strikes. Just go ham on your reel. This puts your bait in front of as many fish as possible without giving them the opportunity to analyze your bait, so instinct will takeover.'.

node.text: A little breakdown on these two similar looking rigs! Which do you prefer?

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Karl’s Bait & Tackle on July 25, 2021. May be an image of one or more people, beard and text that says 'Karl's FISHING 101: TEXAS RIG vs. CAROLINA RIG'.

Photo by Karl’s Bait & Tackle on July 25, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'THE DIFFERENCE Texas Rig: Bullet weight Soft plastic 白 Hook Bead Carolina Rig: Leader line Soft plastic Bullet- Swivel weight Hook *Bobbér stops are optional for both rigs'.

Photo by Karl’s Bait & Tackle on July 25, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'QUALITIES Texas: -Quicker to setup -a more compact presentation -Good for flipping and pitching -Versitile/ can be used many ways Carolina: -Mainly a bottom fishing technique Holds bait right above the bottom Easier to cast deeper But still good in shallow water More subtle action'.

Photo by Karl’s Bait & Tackle on July 25, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'WHERE TO FISH IT Both of these rigs can be used in countless ways. Here are some popular ones: Texas: -Heavy cover -Vegetation -Rocks -Matted grass -Any depth Carolina: -Along structure -Offshore -Deep water -Currents -Cold water -Open water'.

Photo by Karl’s Bait & Tackle on July 25, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'HOW TO FISH IT Texas: -Steady streamlined retrieve -Drag/hop along the bottom -Rig it weightless and swim it -Flip and pitch like a jig' Carolina: -Drag it along the bottom -Hop it over. rocks/ the bottom -Add pauses to these styles if needed'.

Photo by Karl’s Bait & Tackle on July 25, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'HOOKS & WEIGHTS Base your hooks selection on what soft plastic you're using. Base your weight selection on your conditions or how you want to fish it. General weight guide: -1/8 oz = slow falling in the shallow -1/4, 5/16, 3/8 Oz sparse cover -1/2 oz = pitching in thick cover 1/2 oz = bass holding 20+ feet deep -11/2 oz = punching matted grass'.

Photo by Karl’s Bait & Tackle on July 25, 2021. May be an image of one or more people, beard and text that says 'SETUP There are a lot of right setup answers for these rigs, so for the most part, use what you're comfortable with! A good guide is to base your setup on how heavy your rig is. Lighter rig = lighter line/rod. Heavy rig MAKE SURE YOU SAVE IT heavier line/rod.'.
Photo by Karl’s Bait & Tackle on July 25, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'KARL'S POWER RANKINGS Best ways to eat fish: Ina a taco 2. Fried 1. DEEP FRIED'.
